abstract = {Abstract  The objective of this paper is to characterize$\backslash$ndynamic pressure traces measured at self-excited combustion instabilities$\backslash$noccurring in two combustion systems of different hardware. One system$\backslash$nis a model lean premixed gas turbine combustor and the other a fullscale$\backslash$nbipropellant liquid rocket thrust chamber. It is commonly observed$\backslash$nin both systems that low frequency waves at around 300Hz are first$\backslash$nexcited at the onset of combustion instabilities and after a short$\backslash$nduration, the instability mode becomes coupled to the resonant acoustic$\backslash$nmodes of the combustion chamber, the first longitudinal mode for$\backslash$nthe lean premixed combustor and the first tangential mode for the$\backslash$nrocket thrust chamber. Low frequency waves seem to get excited at$\backslash$nfirst since flame shows the higher heat release response on the lower$\backslash$nfrequency perturbations with the smaller phase differences between$\backslash$nheat release and pressure fluctuations. Nonlinear time series analysis$\backslash$nof pressure traces reveals that even stable combustion might have$\backslash$nchaotic behavior with the positive maximum Lyapunov exponent. Also,$\backslash$npressure fluctuations under combustion instabilities reach a limit$\backslash$ncycle or quasi-periodic oscillations at the very similar run conditions,$\backslash$nwhich manifest that a self-excited high frequency instability has$\backslash$nstrong nonlinear characteristics.},
