@book{Takens2010a,
abstract = {This chapter reviews the new methods of time series analysis based on embedding theory and correlation integrals. These methods and the relations of these methods with linear methods, are well understood and supported by mathematical theory. The chapter presents an experimental example, a dripping tap, which gives a good heuristic idea of the method of reconstruction. It describes the reconstruction theorem which gives, amongst others, a justification for this analysis of the dripping tap. It also motivates a method for deriving numerical invariants, which can be used to characterize the dynamics of the system generating a time series. Some notions related to stationarity, in particular the so-called reconstruction measures are introduced, which describe the statistics of the behavior of a time series as far as subsegments (of small lengths) are concerned. The chapter discusses the correlation integrals and the dimensions and entropies which are based on them, and relates the methods in terms of correlation integrals with linear methods. A short discussion of related topics is presented which, however, do not strictly fall within the framework of the analysis of time series in terms of correlation integrals.},
