abstract = {Three methods of nonlinear time series analysis, Lempel-Ziv complexity,$\backslash$nprediction error and covariance complexity were employed to distinguish$\backslash$nbetween the electroencephalograms (EEGs) of normal children, children$\backslash$nwith mild autism, and children with severe autism. Five EEG tracings per$\backslash$ncluster of children aged three to seven medically diagnosed with mild,$\backslash$nsevere and no autism were used in the analysis. A general trend seen was$\backslash$nthat the EEGs of children with mild autism were significantly different$\backslash$nfrom those with severe or no autism. No significant difference was$\backslash$nobserved between normal children and children with severe autism. Among$\backslash$nthe three methods used, the method that was best able to distinguish$\backslash$nbetween EEG tracings of children with mild and severe autism was found$\backslash$nto be the prediction error, with a t-Test confidence level of above$\backslash$n98{\%}.},
