@article{Hacki2013,
abstract = {Introduction: Heart rate variability (HRV) has been used in clinical studies to determine alterations in heart function. The deleterious effects of smoking on the cardiovascular system have also been reported extensively. In this study, we tested the hypothesis that long term active exposure to tobacco smoke triggers an irreversible change in the adaptability of the cardiovascular system, and that this effect may be reflected in alterations of HRV. Methods: We applied a novel method from the field of nonlinear time series analysis on series of inter beat intervals, in order to characterize the predictability of the heart rate. There is a parameter, known as the maximal Lyapunov exponent (coefficient lambda), that can be interpreted as a measure of the adaptability of the cardiovascular system. By using multivariable regression models on this parameter, we were able to explore the association between HRV and tobacco smoke exposure. The datasets were part of the SAPALDIA (Swiss Cohort Study on Air Pollution and Lung and Heart Diseases in Adults) cohort study, which contains 24h ECG data for 1586 participants and information about tobacco smoke exposure and further covariates such as biometric and disease related variables. Results: The covariates cigarettes per day and pack-years were significantly associated with lower lambda coefficients, indicating higher predictability of heart rate among smokers. The effect was similar when we analyzed ex-smokers and current smokers separately. Conclusion: Smoking is associated with a significant increase in heart rate predictability, irrespectively of the current smoking status. Therefore, direct long term exposure to tobacco smoke may fundamentally affect the adaptability of the cardiovascular system.},
